title: For Sale:  Italian Carcano 7.35mm carbine, antique
postcontent: Italian manufactured 7.35x51mm carbine.  It may have been made for civilian sporting use or the stock could be after-factory - I don't know.  I can only locate one serial number on the entire rifle and it's on the breech ring.  There appear to be Italian cartouches, including a crown, and proof marks - they are faded and shallow.  The year 1938 and the numerals "XVIII" are also stamped into the action.  It appears similar to the 1891 cavalry carbine.  There is no provision for a cleaning rod or mounting a bayonet.  The bluing is about 80% and there is some pitting.  I have not fired this rifle since acquiring it because I don't stock 7.35mm ammo.

title: For Sale:  Prohibition Era Winchester Model 12 Short-Barreled Shotgun
postcontent:
I have here a neat old Winchester model 12 with a short barrel, long magazine and compensator.  It is fully functional; I have fired it a few times over the years.  According to the serial number of 350XXX, it was manufactured early in 1924, during the early prohibition era.  I like to picture it being held by Eliot Ness... it was really looking good in my display cabinet next to a Thompson reproduction I used to have!

The action works great, and the slide is quite smooth.   The receiver is steel, unlike newer shotguns that are all aluminum.  I believe the tube magazine holds 6+1.  The walnut stock and pump are beautiful - like a 100 year old piece of furniture.  There is no heavy rust or pitting, but that being said there is almost no bluing left either.  The gun has a nice patina, and is very cool looking in person.  It's also heavy, being all steel, even with the short barrel it weighs in at about 7 pounds.  The butt plate is heavy steel as well.  The recoil is not bad at all due to the weight.

Please e-mail me with your phone number if you want to come take a look.  I'm located in North Skagit County, but I work in Mt Vernon, and travel south to Seattle from time to time.   I'm going to want to see a CWP and ID for the private transfer.

I'm not really looking for any trades at this time, but it never hurts to ask!  Thanks for looking, and have a great day!
